  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A charting tool that measures retracement levels within a price swing, using key ratios (0.5, 0.618, 0.705, 0.79, 1.0) to define premium/discount zones and the Optimal Trade Entry (OTE) zone. The 0.5 level separates discount (below) from premium (above). In ICT, it is applied to breaker blocks, FVGs, and swing ranges to identify high-probability entry areas.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Configure the Fibonacci retracement tool with levels 0.5, 0.62, 0.705, 0.79, and 1.0.",
    "Identify a confirmed swing high and swing low that define the range to be measured.",
    "For a bearish scenario, drag the tool from the swing high down to the swing low; for a bullish scenario, drag from the swing low up to the swing high.",
    "Mark the 0.5 level as the equilibrium boundary between discount and premium.",
    "Mark the zone from 0.62 to 0.79, including the 0.705 midpoint, as the Optimal Trade Entry (OTE) zone.",
    "In an uptrend, the discount zone (below 50%) is the buying area, with optimal buy entries between the 61.8% and 78.6% retracement levels. In a downtrend, the premium zone (above 50%) is the selling area, with optimal sell entries between the 61.8% and 78.6% retracement levels.",
    "A pullback is valid only if it retraces at least to the 38.2% Fibonacci level; failure to reach 38.2% treats the entire move as a single leg without valid swing points.",
    "Swing low or swing high is confirmed only after a break of structure that follows a valid pullback reaching at least the 38.2% retracement.",
    "When applying to breaker blocks, draw from the close of the candle to the low/high to mark the 0.5 level.",
    "When applying to FVGs, use the Fibonacci tool to mark the 50% geometric midpoint for refined entries."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "After a swing range forms, wait for price to retrace into the OTE zone (0.62–0.79) before seeking entries. In a bearish range, look for short entries targeting sellside liquidity below; in a bullish range, look for long entries targeting buyside liquidity or FVG above. Combine with PD Arrays (Order Blocks, FVGs) for confluence. The 0.705 midpoint is a high-probability reaction level. Entering in discount (buy) or premium (sell) improves risk-reward.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Drawing the tool before both a swing high and swing low are confirmed; the retracement must wait until the range is fully formed.",
    "Drawing in the wrong direction for the scenario (high-to-low is for bearish, low-to-high is for bullish).",
    "Placing orders at Fibonacci levels without additional confluence, reducing accuracy.",
    "Aiming for excessively deep retracements (e.g., 78.6%) and missing trades because price does not reach that level.",
    "Using Fibonacci retracement in isolation without aligning with market structure and premium/discount zones.",
    "Misidentifying premium and discount zones, leading to buying in the premium or selling in the discount.",
    "Failing to adjust the Fibonacci tool when the impulse wave extends further, leading to incorrect zone placement.",
    "Entering too early (e.g., in premium during an uptrend) without waiting for price to reach the discount zone.",
    "Mistaking a shallow retracement (below 38.2%) as a valid pullback, leading to premature reversal expectations.",
    "Marking swing points before a break of structure, which can falsely indicate a reversal.",
    "Using default Fibonacci settings with all levels, which clutters the chart and obscures key reversal zones.",
    "Anchoring the tool from arbitrary points rather than clear swing highs and lows.",
    "Inconsistently mixing wick-to-wick and body-to-body drawing methods.",
    "Only using candle body without considering wicks when calculating 0.5 Fib level on breaker blocks.",
    "Expecting a reaction after price has already crossed the 0.5 Fib level; confirm on touch without penetration.",
    "Entering at equilibrium (0.5) instead of waiting for discount/premium zones, resulting in poor risk-reward.",
    "Failing to update Fibonacci range as price makes new highs/lows, using outdated zones.",
    "Ignoring Order Block mean threshold when OB open price is outside OTE zone."
  ],
